english:
  title: Ode in Praise of Avalokiteshvara at Naksan
  author: Kim Gu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    With eyes infinite and arms without end, the Bodhisattva manifests her responsive way through countless worlds and infinite particles of dust. Dwelling neither in thought nor in emptiness, she reveals her compassionate response to all beings and all things. How we gaze upon her painted image, her sculpted form—with hearts truly sincere and reverent. Yet the direct encounter with voice and form stirs a gratitude beyond thought.

    I bow and reflect: what joy is there in rulership? To govern rightly is arduous beyond measure. With ten thousand subjects bearing countless faults, to whom shall I assign the blame? When officials err, is this not the failure of my own virtue? The clouds and sun, the cold and heat—these follow heaven's law, yet my people sometimes resent me. Flood and drought, abundance and famine—these follow the year's decree, yet the world often curses me. And I, but a disciple, have succeeded to this realm after generations of chaos and strife, inheriting a land withered and broken. The desert I never visited even in dreams, yet twice I have endured the hardship of its roads. War itself strikes terror merely by its name, yet I have witnessed invasion and turmoil many times. Though I now receive some pity from the great kingdom above, still I fall short of fulfilling the imperial mandate of old. Heaven's clouds and clearing shift within moments—how can I know what love or hate the world bears come evening? Alas, my emissary departed and has not returned beyond the appointed time. In my private anxiety, I fear some calamity delays him there. Not only are external dangers thus, but internal troubles also afflict the realm. Governance and law have fallen into chaos, customs decay, treasures and grain are exhausted—both public and private coffers are impoverished. This stems from the failure of human effort to cultivate virtue, drawing down the signs of calamity. The moon and stars lose their courses—why do reports of this multiply? Thunder and rain come out of season—can these be auspicious omens? We fear famine, plague, and war; the worry and toil of day and night know no end. I recall the ruins of the past and contemplate trials yet to come. I seek only the merciful protection of the Bodhisattva, that blessings may be prolonged and extended.

    Consider: at Potalaka, at Naksan, dwells the Compassionate Avalokiteshvara. Her gentle countenance was consumed when wildfire swept through the temple. Yet now a new sanctuary has risen from the cliff face. The walls stand complete. We sought skilled artisans to fashion her noble likeness. The great work is finished, the consecration ceremony prepared. My heart returns to that jeweled mountain where a solitary cloud neither comes nor goes, and the moon's reflection in the clear pond—how different is this ancient instant from all time? I have purified the palace halls and gathered the awakened sangha. Some chant the sacred name of Great Compassion; others expound the direct pointing to Buddha-mind. Ten directions ring with drums—the true hearing of enlightenment flows unobstructed everywhere. In one place bells sound—the wondrous play of empty hands unfolds. With pure devotion and sincere heart, wisdom's light reaches the crown of my head.

    I bow and pray: may heaven's demons and earth's portents scatter and dissolve. May the ancestral kingdom and national foundation endure eternally. May neighboring lands grow ever more friendly, the borders know no tremor. May years accumulate in length, and the palace find peace and good fortune. May generals and ministers of both courts harmonize, while traitors both within and without crumble to dust. May the three luminaries run their courses true, the seven calamities break and fade. Then shall the throne be held secure and complete, and the protection of dharma be constant and whole.
  footnotes:
    - Potalaka (補陁洛) traditionally refers to the mythical mountain abode of Avalokiteshvara in Indian Buddhist cosmology. Here it refers to Naksan (洛山), site of the famous Naksan-sa temple in Korea, believed to be an earthly manifestation of this sacred place.
    - 'The ''seven calamities'' (七難) refers to the seven disasters mentioned in Buddhist scriptures: famine, war, plague, injustice, astronomical anomalies, and celestial disturbances.'
    - This text is a dedicatory prayer (疏) for the consecration of a newly sculpted image of Avalokiteshvara at Naksan Temple, blending royal concerns with Buddhist devotion.
